Description: 694 – At the Seventeenth Council of Toledo, Egica, a king of the Visigoths of Hispania, accuses Jews of aiding Muslims, sentencing all Jews to slavery.

Name: Battle of Fujigawa
Description: 1180 – The Battle of Fujigawa: Minamoto forces (30,000 men) under Minamoto no Yoritomo defeat Taira no Koremori during a night attack near the Fuji River but he escapes safely with the routed army.

Name: Treaty of Aberconwy
Description: 1277 – The Treaty of Aberconwy, a humiliating settlement forced on Llywelyn ap Gruffudd by King Edward I of England, brings a temporary end to the Welsh Wars.

Name: Knights Templar
Description: 1307 – Knights Templar officer Hugues de Pairaud is forced to confess during the Trials of the Knights Templar. He was persecuted on the charges of false idolism and sodomy.

Name: Louis the Bavarian
Description: 1313 – Louis the Bavarian defeats his cousin Frederick I of Austria at the Battle of Gammelsdorf.

Name: Siege of Warangal
Description: 1323 – Siege of Warangal: Prataparudra surrenders to Muhammad bin Tughlaq, officially marking the end of the Kakatiya dynasty.

Name: Battle of Posada
Description: 1330 – At the Battle of Posada, Basarab I of Wallachia defeats the Hungarian army of Charles I Robert.

Name: Trần Duệ Tông
Description: 1372 – Trần Duệ Tông succeeds his brother Trần Nghệ Tông as King of Vietnam.

Name: Battle of Ilava
Description: 1431 – The Battle of Ilava: The Hungarians defeat the Hussite army.

Name: Ulrich II, Count of Celje
Description: 1456 – Ulrich II, Count of Celje, last ruler of the County of Cilli, is assassinated in Belgrade.

Name: Stockholm Bloodbath
Description: 1520 – More than 50 people are sentenced and executed in the Stockholm Bloodbath.

Name: Second Desmond Rebellion
Description: 1580 – Second Desmond Rebellion: The Siege of Smerwick ends with the Catholic garrison surrendering to the English forces under Arthur Grey. The majority of the garrison is massacred the next day.

Name: Battle of White Mountain
Description: 1620 – The Bohemian King Frederick I flees Prague to Wroclaw one day after the defeat of his troops in the Battle of White Mountain.

Name: Glorious Revolution
Description: 1688 – Glorious Revolution: William of Orange captures Exeter.

Name: a treaty between Sweden and Hanover
Description: 1719 – In a treaty between Sweden and Hanover at the close of the Great Northern War, Sweden cedes the  Duchies of Bremen and Verden (in northern Germany) to Hanover.

Name: Judah HeHasid
Description: 1720 – The synagogue of Judah HeHasid is burned down by Arab creditors, leading to the expulsion of the Ashkenazim from Jerusalem.

Name: Treaty of Seville
Description: 1729 – Spain, France and Great Britain sign the Treaty of Seville.

Name: American Revolutionary War
Description: 1780 – American Revolutionary War: In the Battle of Fishdam Ford a force of British and Loyalist troops fail in a surprise attack against the South Carolina Patriot militia under Brigadier General Thomas Sumter.

Name: Society of United Irishmen
Description: 1791 – The Dublin Society of United Irishmen is founded.

Name: Coup of 18 Brumaire
Description: 1799 – Napoleon Bonaparte leads the Coup of 18 Brumaire ending the Directory government, and becoming First Consul of the successor Consulate Government.

Name: Kentucky
Description: 1851 – Kentucky marshals abduct abolitionist minister Calvin Fairbank from Jeffersonville, Indiana, and take him to Kentucky to stand trial for helping a slave escape.

Name: American Civil War
Description: 1862 – American Civil War: Union General Ambrose Burnside assumes command of the Army of the Potomac, after George B. McClellan is removed.

Name: Tokugawa shogunate
Description: 1867 – The Tokugawa shogunate hands back power to the Emperor of Japan, starting the Meiji Restoration.

Name: Battle of Coulmiers
Description: 1870 – The Battle of Coulmiers ends in a Pyrrhic victory for the French army during the Franco-German War of 1870.

Name: Great Boston Fire of 1872
Description: 1872 – The Great Boston Fire of 1872.

Name: major earthquake
Description: 1880 – A major earthquake strikes Zagreb and destroys many buildings, including Zagreb Cathedral.

Name: Mapuche rebels
Description: 1881 – Mapuche rebels attack the fortified Chilean settlement of Temuco.

Name: Pearl Harbor
Description: 1887 – The United States receives rights to Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.

Name: Jack the Ripper
Description: 1888 – Jack the Ripper murders Mary Jane Kelly, his final victim in the Whitechapel murders.

Name: Russian invasion of Manchuria
Description: 1900 – Russian invasion of Manchuria: Russia completes its occupation of Manchuria with 100,000 troops.

Name: Duke of Cornwall
Description: 1901 – Prince George, Duke of Cornwall (later George V of the United Kingdom), becomes Prince of Wales and Earl of Chester.

Name: Alberta
Description: 1905 – The Province of Alberta, Canada, holds its first general election.

Name: Theodore Roosevelt
Description: 1906 – Theodore Roosevelt is the first sitting President of the United States to make an official trip outside the country, doing so to inspect progress on the Panama Canal.

Name: Cullinan Diamond
Description: 1907 – The Cullinan Diamond is presented to King Edward VII on his birthday.

Name: Great Lakes Storm of 1913
Description: 1913 – The Great Lakes Storm of 1913, the most destructive natural disaster ever to hit the lakes, reaches its greatest intensity after beginning two days earlier. The storm destroys 19 ships and kills more than 250 people.

Name: SMS Emden
Description: 1914 – SMS Emden is sunk by HMAS Sydney in the Battle of Cocos.

Name: Balfour Declaration
Description: 1917 – The Balfour Declaration is published in The Times newspaper.

Name: Kaiser
Description: 1918 – Kaiser Wilhelm II of Germany abdicates after the German Revolution, and Germany is proclaimed a Republic.

Name: National Fascist Party
Description: 1921 – The National Fascist Party (Partito Nazionale Fascista or PNF) is founded in Italy.

Name: Munich
Description: 1923 – In Munich, police and government troops crush the Nazi Beer Hall Putsch.

Name: Congress of Industrial Organizations
Description: 1935 – The Committee for Industrial Organization, the precursor to the Congress of Industrial Organizations, is founded in Atlantic City, New Jersey, by eight trade unions belonging to the American Federation of Labor.

Name: Ruth Harkness
Description: 1936 – American fashion designer Ruth Harkness encounters and captures a nine-week-old panda cub in Sichuan; it becomes the first live giant panda to enter the United States.

Name: Second Sino-Japanese War
Description: 1937 – Second Sino-Japanese War: The Chinese Army withdraws from the Battle of Shanghai.

Name: Kristallnacht
Description: 1938 – Kristallnacht occurs, instigated by the Nazis using the killing of German diplomat Ernst vom Rath by Herschel Grynszpan as justification.

Name: Warsaw
Description: 1940 – Warsaw is awarded the Virtuti Militari by the Polish government-in-exile.

Name: Battle of Stalingrad
Description: 1942 – Battle of Stalingrad: German forces of the 6th Army under general Friedrich Paulus reach finally the river bank of the Volga, capturing 90% of the ruined city of Stalingrad and splitting the remaining Soviet forces into two narrow pockets.

Name: White House
Description: 1943 – An agreement for the founding of the United Nations Relief and Rehabilitation Administration is signed by 44 countries in the White House, Washington, D.C.

Name: Soo Bahk Do
Description: 1945 – Soo Bahk Do and Moo Duk Kwan martial arts are founded in Korea.

Name: Cambodia
Description: 1953 – Cambodia gains independence from France.

Name: Robert McNamara
Description: 1960 – Robert McNamara is named president of the Ford Motor Company, becoming the first non-Ford family member to serve in that post. He resigns a month later to join the newly elected John F. Kennedy administration.

Name: coal mine
Description: 1963 – At a coal mine in Miike, Japan, an explosion kills 458 and hospitalises 839 with carbon monoxide poisoning.

Name: blackouts
Description: 1965 – Several U.S. states and parts of Canada are hit by a series of blackouts lasting up to 13 hours in the Northeast blackout of 1965.

Name: Catholic Worker Movement
Description: 1965   – A Catholic Worker Movement member, Roger Allen LaPorte, protesting against the Vietnam War, sets himself on fire in front of the United Nations building.

Name: Apollo program
Description: 1967 – Apollo program: NASA launches the unmanned Apollo 4 test spacecraft, atop the first Saturn V rocket, from Florida's Cape Kennedy.

Name: Vietnam War
Description: 1970 – Vietnam War: The Supreme Court of the United States votes 6–3 against hearing a case to allow Massachusetts to enforce its law granting residents the right to refuse military service in an undeclared war.

Name: John List
Description: 1971 – American banker John List murdered his wife, mother, and three children with a pair of handguns.

Name: Cold War
Description: 1979 – Cold War: Nuclear false alarm: The NORAD computers and the Alternate National Military Command Center in Fort Ritchie, Maryland, detect a purported massive Soviet nuclear strike. After reviewing the raw data from satellites and checking the early-warning radars, the alert is cancelled.

Name: Garry Kasparov
Description: 1985 – Garry Kasparov, 22, of the Soviet Union, becomes the youngest World Chess Champion by beating fellow Soviet Anatoly Karpov.

Name: Fall of the Berlin Wall
Description: 1989 – Cold War: Fall of the Berlin Wall: East Germany opens checkpoints in the Berlin Wall, allowing its citizens to travel to West Berlin.

Name: Stari Most
Description: 1993 – Stari Most, the "old bridge" in the Bosnian city of Mostar, built in 1566, collapses after several days of bombing by Croat forces during the Croat–Bosniak War.

Name: chemical element
Description: 1994 – The chemical element darmstadtium is discovered.

Name: NASDAQ
Description: 1998 – A U.S. federal judge, in the largest civil settlement in American history, orders 37 U.S. brokerage houses to pay US$1.03 billion to cheated NASDAQ investors to compensate for price fixing.

Name: Capital punishment in the United Kingdom
Description: 1998   – Capital punishment in the United Kingdom, already abolished for murder, is completely abolished for all remaining capital offences.

Name: TAESA Flight 725
Description: 1999 – TAESA Flight 725 crashes after takeoff from Uruapan International Airport in Uruapan, Michoacán, Mexico, killing all 18 people on board.

Name: Uttarakhand
Description: 2000 – Uttarakhand officially becomes the 27th state of India, formed from thirteen districts of northwestern Uttar Pradesh.

Name: Firefox
Description: 2004 – Firefox 1.0 is released.

Name: Venus Express
Description: 2005 – The Venus Express mission of the European Space Agency is launched from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan.

Name: Suicide bombers attack
Description: 2005   – Suicide bombers attack three hotels in Amman, Jordan, killing at least 60 people.

Name: Emergency Alert System
Description: 2011 - The first national test of the Emergency Alert System is activated in the United States at 2:00 p.m. EST.

Name: crashes and bursts into flames
Description: 2012 – A train carrying liquid fuel crashes and bursts into flames in northern Myanmar, killing 27 people and injuring 80 others.

Name: conflicts
Description: 2012   – At least 27 people are killed and dozens are wounded in conflicts between inmates and guards at Welikada prison in Colombo.

Name: non-binding self-determination consultation
Description: 2014 – A non-binding self-determination consultation is held in Catalonia, asking Catalan citizens their opinion on whether Catalonia should become a state and, if so, whether it should be an independent state.

Name: Second Nagorno-Karabakh War
Description: 2020 – Second Nagorno-Karabakh War: An armistice agreement is signed by Armenia, Azerbaijan and Russia.

Name: NYU Langone Health
Description: 2023 – U.S. surgeons at NYU Langone Health announce the world's first whole eye transplant.
